      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "According to Diod. Sic. i. 56, Sesostris (Rameses II.), the great Egyptian monarch, was wont to inscribe over the temples he built, “No native hath laboured hereon.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After “men of war,” Kings adds, “and his servants,” which is omitted here as unsuitable, after the preceding statement. It means, however, courtiers and officers.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Chief of his captains.—Heb., captains of his knights; which appears to be incorrect. Read, “his captains and his knights,” or “aides-de-camp.” as in Kings. LXX., καὶ ἄρχοντες καὶ δυνατοὶ.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Chief of his captains.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Heb., ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "captains of his knights;",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " which appears to be incorrect. Read, “his captains and his knights,” or “aides-de-camp.” as in Kings. LXX., ",
            "children": []
